<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – The U.S. dollar was broadly lower against its major counterparts on Tuesday, with the euro and pound posting strong gains as U.S. markets resumed trading after a three day break.During European late afternoon trade, the greenback was down against the euro, with EUR/USD surging 0.73% to hit 1.339. Earlier Tuesday, the ZEW Centre for Economic Research said its index of German economic sentiment jumped to a six-month high in January.The greenback was also down against sterling with GBP/USD rising 0.64% to hit 1.599. Earlier in the day, the U.K. Office for National Statistics said the annual rate of CPI rose to 3.7% in December from 3.3% in November, much higher than forecasts for a steady reading.Elsewhere, the greenback was up against the yen but down against the Swiss franc, with USD/JPY easing up 0.06% to hit 82.72 and USD/CHF slipping 0.16% to hit 0.9629.Earlier Tuesday, final data from the Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry showed that Japanese industrial production grew 1% in November, confirming the original estimate.Meanwhile, the greenback was up against its Canadian and New Zealand counterparts but up against its Australian cousin, with USD/CAD climbing 0.41% to hit 0.9909, NZD/USD slipping 0.2% to hit 0.7706 and AUD/USD rising 0.4% to hit 0.9976.Earlier Tuesday, the Bank of Canada announced that it was holding its key overnight interest rate steady at 1.00% as expected.The dollar index, which tracks the performance of the greenback versus a basket of six other major currencies, was down 0.49%.Also Tuesday, official data showed that the New York Federal Reserve’s index of manufacturing conditions rose slightly less-than-expected in January, while a separate report said that U.S. Treasury International Capital purchases rose significantly more-than-expected in November.             ]]></raw>
